China's investment relies on
<s>Beijing – China's economy unexpectedly slowed in the second quarter this year.
<s>What is equally surprising is that most data released since July suggests that growth has stabilized.
<s>No wonder the markets heaved a collective sigh of relief.
<s>Should investors remain on edge?
Currently, the most severe problem facing China's authorities is overcapacity.
For example, China's annual steel production capacity is ten billion tons, but the total production in 2012 was only 720 million tons — utilization rate was 72%.
More strikingly, the steel industry's profit margin in 2012 was only 0.04%.
In fact, the profit earned per ton of steel production could buy only a lollipop.
So far this year, the average profit margin of China's top 500 companies was 4.34%, down 33 basis points from 2012.
<s>Some say today's overcapacity comes from past overinvestment.
<s>Others believe overcapacity is due to insufficient effective demand.
<s>The government's view seems to be a compromise between the two.
<s>On one hand, authorities are asking thousands of companies to cut their capacity.
<s>On the other hand, the government has introduced some "mini-stimulus" measures, such as exempting micro-enterprises from business tax and value-added tax, and requiring banks to increase loans to export firms.
<s>Authorities' official stance is that China's growth model needs to reduce investment and increase consumption.




<s>According to official statistics, China's investment rate has approached 50% of GDP.
<s>Thanks to diminishing returns, capital efficiency declines steadily with larger capital stock.
<s>Considering the environmental damage caused by the rapid growth in investment, China's capital efficiency would be even lower.
<s>Human capital and technological progress play no less important a role in economic growth than physical capital and labor.
<s>If resources are allocated towards physical capital at the expense of human capital accumulation — which is essential for sustained consumption — economic growth is more likely to slow rather than accelerate.
<s>Therefore, China should lower its investment growth rate and raise its consumption growth rate, stabilizing the investment rate at a more sustainable level.
<s>Naturally, it is not entirely wrong to say that China's excess capacity reflects a lack of effective demand.
<s>But where does effective demand come from?
<s>In this aspect, the Chinese steel industry again provides a good example.
<s>Despite having no comparative advantage in steel production, China built approximately one thousand steel plants, accounting for half of the global output.
<s>Back in 2004, the Chinese government tried to cool down excessive investment; but robust demand driven by infrastructure investment and real estate development kept production growing rapidly, from 300 million tons in that year to 1 billion tons by 2012.
<s>Chinese investment can roughly be divided into three categories: manufacturing, infrastructure, and real estate.
<s>At the peak of the global financial crisis in late 2008 and 2009, infrastructure investments spurred by economic stimulus maintained the growth in output.
<s>In 2010, real estate development investment became the main driver of growth, replacing infrastructure investment.
<s>Today, both infrastructure and real estate continue to be key drivers of China's growth.
<s>China certainly needs more infrastructure investment — particularly in power and hydropower, transportation, and communications.
<s>But the pace of investment must take financial constraints sufficiently into account.
<s>More importantly, China can and should invest more in social infrastructure such as schools, hospitals, and nursing homes.
<s>But housing investment is a different matter.
<s>It is difficult to judge the severity of the housing bubble and when it will burst.
But one thing is certain: China has invested too much in real estate development.
Per capita income in China is less than $6,000, yet the homeownership rate is as high as 90%, compared to less than 70% in the United States.
The average per capita housing area is 32.9 square meters, while the median family home size in Hong Kong is just 48 square meters.
China has 696 five-star hotels, and another 500 are under construction.
Of the ten tallest buildings under construction in the world, five are in China.
<s>In my view, this can only be described as madness.
<s>China’s economy is being held hostage by real estate investments.
<s>On one hand, China should not rely on maintaining a high growth rate of real estate investments to address overcapacity.
<s>Social housing projects are welcome, but the current real estate investments amounting to 10-13% of GDP are already too high.
<s>On the other hand, if real estate investments were to slow down, overcapacity could not be eliminated.
<s>This dilemma highlights the structural adjustment challenges China faces—also reason enough for investors to remain cautious.
<s>Overall, there are two things worth watching out for.
<s>First, unlike other types of investment, real estate investment does not increase productive capital stock.
<s>There is little difference fundamentally between houses and expensive durables.
<s>Second, in China's statistics, the growth rate of total fixed asset investment is significantly higher than that of gross capital formation.
This indicates that the growth rate data of fixed investment may overstate the speed of accumulating capital stock.
Therefore, while the Chinese government should decisively reduce its reliance on investment for growth, actions must be very cautious.
